[{"id":29427,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Electrochemistry","question":"","options":["only gold","silver and gold in proportion to their atomic weights","only silver","silver and gold in equal mass proportion"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>&#160;Charge&#160;</mtext><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">q</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mtext>&#160;it&#160;</mtext><mn>96500</mn></mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>15</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>60</mn></mrow><mn>96500</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>900</mn><mn>96500</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>9</mn><mn>965</mn></mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>0093</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi></math></p><p>No. of moles of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Au</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>025</mn></math>&nbsp;&amp; No. of moles of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Ag</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>025</mn></math></p><p>Species with higher value of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>SRP</mi></math> will get deposited first at cathode.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi>Au</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><mo>(</mo><mi>aqs</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>+</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mo>-</mo></msup><mo>&#10230;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Au</mi><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>)</mo></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>025</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>0093</mn></math>&nbsp;mole&nbsp;</p><p>so only&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Au</mi></math> will get deposited.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (04 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29400,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Electrochemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>For KCl solution, R = 1750 ohms</p><p>Conductivity, K =<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>152</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><msup><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p>K=<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></mfrac></mfenced><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></mfrac></math></p><p>Cell constant,<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>XR</mi></math>=<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>152</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>1750</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>266</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><msup><mi>cm</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (24 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29336,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Electrochemistry","question":"","options":["reduction of \\(\\mathrm{Mn}\\) from +7 to +2","reduction of \\(\\mathrm{Mn}\\) from +4 to +3","oxidation of \\(\\mathrm{Mn}\\) from +3 to +4","oxidation of \\(\\mathrm{Mn}\\) from +2 to +7"],"answer":1,"solution":"In the cathode reaction manganese $(\\mathrm{Mn})$ is reduced from the +4 oxidation state to the +3 state.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (05 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29363,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Electrochemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>HCl</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NaOH</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Cl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The aqueous solution of sodium chloride is known as brine solution. On electrolysis of brine solution, the following reactions are observed.</p><p>Oxidation reaction takes place at anode and reduction reaction takes place at cathode. The reaction</p><p>Anode:&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><msup><mi>OH</mi><mo>-</mo></msup><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mo>&#8861;</mo></msup></math></p><p>Cathode:&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mo>&#8861;</mo></msup><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msup><mi>OH</mi><mo>&#8861;</mo></msup></math></p><p>Hydrogen and oxygen are electrode products. The remaining solution contain&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NaOH</mi></math>.</p><p>Hence, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>HCl</mi></math>&nbsp;is not obtained</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (06 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29359,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Electrochemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>An intensive property is a bulk property, meaning that it is a physical property of a system that does not depend on the system size or the amount of material in the system.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#916;G</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>&#8722;</mo><msub><mi>nFE</mi><mi>cell</mi></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#8203;</mo></math></p><p>The&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8710;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">G</mi></math>&nbsp;in the above equation is an extensive property,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mi>cell</mi></msub></math>&nbsp;is an intensive property.&nbsp;A negative <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi></msup></math>means that the redox couple is a stronger reducing agent than the&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><mo>/</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>couple.&nbsp;The amount of electricity required for oxidation or reduction depends on the stoichiometry of the electrode reaction.&nbsp;The amount of chemical reaction which occurs at any electrode during electrolysis by a current is proportional to the quantity of electricity passed through the electrolyte.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (11 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29362,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Electrochemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Pt</mi><mo>|</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>|</mo><mi>HCl</mi><mo>(</mo><msup><mi>sol</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>)</mo><mo>|</mo><mi>AgCl</mi><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>|</mo><mi>Ag</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Ag</mi><mo>|</mo><mi>AgCl</mi><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>|</mo><mi>KCl</mi><mo>(</mo><msup><mi>sol</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>)</mo><mo>|</mo><msub><mi>AgNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>|</mo><mi>Ag</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Pt</mi><mo>|</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>|</mo><mi>HCl</mi><mo>(</mo><msup><mi>sol</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>)</mo><mo>|</mo><msub><mi>AgNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>(</mo><msup><mi>sol</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>)</mo><mo>|</mo><mi>Ag</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Pt</mi><mo>|</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><msup><mrow/><mn>2</mn></msup></msub><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>|</mo><mi>KCl</mi><mo>(</mo><msup><mi>sol</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>)</mo><mo>|</mo><mi>AgCl</mi><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>|</mo><mi>Ag</mi></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Oxidation is loss of electron and in a galvanic cell it occurs at anode. Reduction is gain of electron and in a galvanic cell it occurs at cathode.</p><p>At anode :<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>(</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#10230;</mo><munder><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>aq</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></munder><mo>+</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></math></p><p>At cathode&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><munder><mi>AgCl</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></munder><mo>+</mo><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mo>&#175;</mo></mover><mo>&#10230;</mo><mi>Ag</mi><mo>+</mo><munder><msup><mi>Cl</mi><mo>-</mo></msup><mtext>&#160;(aq)&#160;</mtext></munder></math></p><p>Overall reaction</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>(</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>+</mo><mi>AgCl</mi><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#10230;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>*</mo></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mi>Cl</mi><mo>-</mo></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>Ag</mi><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>)</mo></math></p><p>Cell representation :</p><p>Anode / Anode electrolyte || Cathodic electrolyte / Cathode.</p><p>The cell representation for the above cell will be</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Pt</mi><mfenced close=\"|\" open=\"|\"><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>(</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></mfenced><mi>HCl</mi><mfenced><msup><mtext>&#160;soln&#160;</mtext><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></msup></mfenced><mo>|</mo><mi>AgCl</mi><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>|</mo><mi>Ag</mi></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (08 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29368,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Electrochemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Given,<br />Resistivity <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#961;</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mi>&#937;cm</mi></math></p><p>Molarity <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math></p><p>Thus, Molar conductivity of electrolyte&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#955;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></msub></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#961;</mi></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>1000</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>1000</mn><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>25</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>6</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>25</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>4</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi>cm</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi>mol</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (31 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29406,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Electrochemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Cell reaction</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Cu</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup><mo>(</mo><mi>aq</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>+</mo><mi>Zn</mi><mo>&#8652;</mo><mi>Cu</mi><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>+</mo><msup><mi>Zn</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup><mo>(</mo><mi>aq</mi><mo>)</mo></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>04</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"\"><mrow><msubsup><mi>E</mi><mrow><mi>c</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>l</mi><mi>l</mi></mrow><mn>0</mn></msubsup><mo>=</mo><msubsup><mi>E</mi><mrow><mi>C</mi><msup><mi>u</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup><mo>&#8739;</mo><mi>C</mi><mi>u</mi></mrow><mn>0</mn></msubsup><mo>-</mo><msubsup><mi>E</mi><mrow><mi>Z</mi><msup><mi>n</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup><mo>&#8739;</mo><mi>Z</mi><mi>n</mi></mrow><mn>0</mn></msubsup></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>34</mn><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>75</mn><mo>)</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mi>cell</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mi>cell</mi><mn>0</mn></msubsup><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>059</mn></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>log</mi><mfrac><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><msup><mi>Zn</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></mfenced><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><msup><mi>Cu</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></mfenced></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>059</mn></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>log</mi><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>04</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn></mrow></mfrac></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>03</mn><mi>log</mi><mn>2</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>03</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>30</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>0915</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>09</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>109</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Aug Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29429,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Electrochemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Charge&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">q</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mi>it</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>60</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>960</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>960</mn><mn>96000</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>01</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Cr</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>7</mn><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></mrow></msubsup><mo>+</mo><mn>14</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>6</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mo>-</mo></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#8594;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>2</mn><msup><mi>Cr</mi><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>+</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>7</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>01</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>01</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mole</mi></math></p><p>Theoritical mass of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Cr</mi><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>600</mn><mn>96000</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>52</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>173</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></math></p><p>So, efficiency&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">W</mi><mi>actual</mi></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">W</mi><mi>Theoritial</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>104</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>173</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>60</mn><mo>%</mo></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (03 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29289,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Electrochemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"The equation $\\Lambda_m = \\Lambda_m^0 - Ac^{1/2}$ is linear in $c^{1/2}$.<br>Taking two data points: (c=0.04, $\\sqrt{c}$=0.2, $\\Lambda_m$=96.1) and (c=0.25, $\\sqrt{c}$=0.5, $\\Lambda_m$=94.9).<br>Slope = $\\frac{94.9 - 96.1}{0.5 - 0.2} = \\frac{-1.2}{0.3} = -4.0$<br>Since slope = -A, the constant A = 4 S cm² mol⁻¹/(mol/L)^(1/2)","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (28 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29367,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Electrochemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msubsup><mi>MnO</mi><mn>4</mn><mo>-</mo></msubsup><mo>+</mo><mn>8</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>5</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mo>-</mo></msup><mo>&#8652;</mo><msup><mi>Mn</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mo>&#176;</mo><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>059</mn></mrow><mn>5</mn></mfrac><mi>log</mi><mfrac><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><msup><mi>Mn</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></mfenced><mrow><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><msubsup><mi>MnO</mi><mn>4</mn><mo>-</mo></msubsup></mfenced><msup><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></mfenced><mn>8</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>282</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>54</mn><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>059</mn></mrow><mn>5</mn></mfrac><mi>log</mi><mfrac><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mrow><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></mfenced><mn>8</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>258</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>059</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>log</mi><mfrac><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><msup><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></mfenced><mn>8</mn></msup></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mn>21</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>86</mn><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>8</mn><mi>pH</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>pH</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>98</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8771;</mo><mn>3</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (01 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29344,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Electrochemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>The Nernst equation for the given cell reaction <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mo>-</mo></msup><mo>→</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> is </p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mo>=</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mo>°</mo></msup><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>06</mn></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>×</mo><mi>log</mi><mo> </mo><mfrac><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></msub><msup><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>06</mn></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>log</mi><mfrac><mn>2</mn><msup><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mn>1</mn></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>03</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>3</mn><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>009</mn><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>9</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>9</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (01 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29479,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Electrochemistry","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{Mn}^{2+} < \\mathrm{Cl}^{-} < \\mathrm{Cr}^{3+} < \\mathrm{Cr}$","$\\mathrm{Mn}^{2+} < \\mathrm{Cl}^{3+} < \\mathrm{Cl}^{-} < \\mathrm{Cr}$","$\\mathrm{Cr}^{3+} < \\mathrm{Cl}^{-} < \\mathrm{Mn}^{2+} < \\mathrm{Cr}$","$\\mathrm{Cr}^{3+} < \\mathrm{Cl}^{-} < \\mathrm{Cr} < \\mathrm{Mn}^{2+}$"],"answer":0,"solution":"Lower the value of reduction potential higher will be reducing power hence the correct order will be\n$$\n\\mathrm{Mn}^{2+} < \\mathrm{Cl}^{-} < \\mathrm{Cr}^{3+} < \\mathrm{Cr}\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (23 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":29382,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Electrochemistry","question":"","options":["Statement I is correct and Statement II is incorrect","Both Statement I and Statement II are false","Statement I is true but Statement II is false","Statement I is false but Statement II is true"],"answer":1,"solution":"<blockquote><p>For strong electrolytes,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mo>&and;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></msub></math>&nbsp;increases slowly with dilution and can be represented by the equation:</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mo>&and;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msubsup><mo>&and;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi></msubsup><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&nbsp;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></msup></math></p><p>It can be seen that if we plot&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mo>&and;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></msub></math>&nbsp;against&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></msup></math>, We obtain a straight line with intercept equal to&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mo>&and;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></msub></math>&nbsp;and slope equal to &#39;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>&#39;. The value of the constant &#39;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>&#39; for a given solvent and temperature depends on the type of electrolyte.&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>KI</mi></math>&nbsp;is a strong electrolyte.</p><p>Weak electrolytes like carbonic&nbsp;acid and have lower degree of dissociation at higher concentrations and hence for such electrolytes, the change in&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mo>&and;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></msub></math>&nbsp;with dilution is due to increase in the degree of dissociation and consequently the number of ions in total volume of solution that contains&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>mol</mi></math>&nbsp;of electrolyte. In such cases&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mo>&and;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></msub></math>&nbsp;increases steeply on dilution, especially near lower concentrations. Therefore,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msubsup><mo>&and;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi></msubsup></math>&nbsp;cannot be obtained by extrapolation&nbsp;of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mo>&and;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></msub></math>&nbsp;to zero concentration.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d09c56b5-375b-488c-984e-bd9b9363c7a8-image.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 149px;\" /></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (27 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29408,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Electrochemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/771db111-b817-45a2-a282-256ba71bdf48-image.png\" style=\"width: 334px; height: 154px;\" /></p><p>So reduction potential depends on sublimation, ionisation and Hydration energy.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Aug Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29454,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Electrochemistry","question":"","options":["$2.0$","$0.1$","$0.5$","$1.0$"],"answer":3,"solution":"Reduction at cathode:\n$2 \\mathrm{e}^{-}+2 \\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{O} \\rightarrow \\mathrm{H}_2+2 \\mathrm{OH}^{-}$ \n(valence factor) $\\mathrm{H}_2=2$\nAt NTP $22400 \\mathrm{~mL}$ of $\\mathrm{H}_2=1$ mole of $\\mathrm{H}_2 ~112 \\mathrm{~mL}$ of $\\mathrm{H}_2=\\frac{1}{22400} \\times 112=0.005 \\text { mole of } \\mathrm{H}_2$\nMoles of $\\mathrm{H}_2$ produced\n$\\begin{aligned}\n&=\\frac{\\mathrm{I} \\times \\mathrm{t}}{96500} \\times \\text { mole ratio } \\\\\n&0.005=\\frac{\\mathrm{I} \\times 965}{96500} \\times \\frac{1 \\text { mole of } \\mathrm{H}_2}{2 \\text { mole of }e^{-}} \\\\\n&\\mathrm{I}=1.0 \\mathrm{~A}\n\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr Shift 1 Online)","image":null},{"id":29384,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Electrochemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#923;</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#923;</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#923;</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#923;</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>/</mo><mn>2</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#923;</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#923;</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#923;</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#923;</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#923;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#954;</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>1000</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#923;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></msub><mo>&#8733;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#923;</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#923;</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mfrac><mn>20</mn><mn>80</mn></mfrac><mfrac><mn>10</mn><mn>20</mn></mfrac></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mn>1</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#923;</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#923;</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (25 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29473,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Electrochemistry","question":"","options":["<math> <mrow> <mn>5</mn> <mo>&times;</mo> <mn>1</mn> <msup> <mn>0</mn> <mrow> <mo>-</mo> <mn>4</mn> </mrow> </msup> </mrow> </math>","<math> <mrow> <mn>5</mn> <mo>&times;</mo> <mn>1</mn> <msup> <mn>0</mn> <mrow> <mo>-</mo> <mn>3</mn> </mrow> </msup> </mrow> </math>","<math> <mrow> <mn>5</mn> <mo>&times;</mo> <mn>1</mn> <msup> <mn>0</mn> <mrow> <mn>3</mn> </mrow> </msup> </mrow> </math>","<math> <mrow> <mn>5</mn> <mo>&times;</mo> <mn>1</mn> <msup> <mn>0</mn> <mrow> <mn>2</mn> </mrow> </msup> </mrow> </math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<math> <mrow> <mtext>K</mtext> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> <mrow> <mtext>R</mtext> </mrow> </mfrac> <mfenced close=\")\" open=\"(\" separators=\",\"> <mrow> <mfrac> <mrow> <mtext mathvariant=\"italic\">l</mtext> </mrow> <mrow> <mtext>a</mtext> </mrow> </mfrac> </mrow> </mfenced> </mrow> </math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <msub> <mtext>K</mtext> <mfenced close=\")\" open=\"(\" separators=\",\"> <mrow> <mtext>0.2 M</mtext> </mrow> </mfenced> </msub> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> <mrow> <mn>5</mn> <mn>0</mn> </mrow> </mfrac> <mfenced close=\")\" open=\"(\" separators=\",\"> <mrow> <mfrac> <mrow> <mtext mathvariant=\"italic\">l</mtext> </mrow> <mrow> <mtext>a</mtext> </mrow> </mfrac> </mrow> </mfenced> </mrow> </math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; ...... (I)<br /><br /><math> <mrow> <msub> <mtext>K</mtext> <mfenced close=\")\" open=\"(\" separators=\",\"> <mrow> <mtext>0.5 M</mtext> </mrow> </mfenced> </msub> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> <mrow> <mn>28</mn> <mn>0</mn> </mrow> </mfrac> <mfenced close=\")\" open=\"(\" separators=\",\"> <mrow> <mfrac> <mrow> <mtext mathvariant=\"italic\">l</mtext> </mrow> <mrow> <mtext>a</mtext> </mrow> </mfrac> </mrow> </mfenced> </mrow> </math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; ...... (II)<br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mfrac> <mrow> <msub> <mtext>K</mtext> <mfenced close=\")\" open=\"(\" separators=\",\"> <mrow> <mtext>0.5 M</mtext> </mrow> </mfenced> </msub> </mrow> <mrow> <msub> <mtext>K</mtext> <mfenced close=\")\" open=\"(\" separators=\",\"> <mrow> <mtext>0.2 M</mtext> </mrow> </mfenced> </msub> </mrow> </mfrac> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> <mrow> <mn>2</mn> <mn>8</mn> <mn>0</mn> </mrow> </mfrac> <mo>&times;</mo> <mn>5</mn> <mn>0</mn> </mrow> </math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <msub> <mtext>K</mtext> <mfenced close=\")\" open=\"(\" separators=\",\"> <mrow> <mtext>0.5 M</mtext> </mrow> </mfenced> </msub> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mtext>1.4</mtext> </mrow> <mrow> <mn>2</mn> <mn>8</mn> <mn>0</mn> </mrow> </mfrac> <mo>&times;</mo> <mn>5</mn> <mn>0</mn> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> <mrow> <mn>4</mn> </mrow> </mfrac> </mrow> </math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <msub> <mi>&Lambda;</mi> <mtext>m</mtext> </msub> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mtext>K</mtext> </mrow> <mrow> <mtext>C</mtext> </mrow> </mfrac> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> <mrow> <mn>4</mn> </mrow> </mfrac> <mo>&times;</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> <mrow> <mtext>0.5</mtext> <mo>&times;</mo> <mn>1</mn> <msup> <mn>0</mn> <mn>3</mn> </msup> </mrow> </mfrac> <mo>=</mo> <mn>5</mn> <mo>&times;</mo> <mn>1</mn> <msup> <mn>0</mn> <mrow> <mo>-</mo> <mn>4</mn> </mrow> </msup> <msup> <mi>&nbsp;&Omega;</mi> <mn>-1</mn> </msup> <msup> <mo>m</mo> <mn>2</mn> </msup> <msup> <mtext>mol</mtext> <mn>-1</mn> </msup> </mrow> </math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mfenced close=\")\" open=\"(\" separators=\",\"> <mrow> <mtext>C</mtext> <mo>=</mo> <msup> <mtext>concentration in mol/m</mtext> <mn>3</mn> </msup> <mo>=</mo> <mtext>0.5</mtext> <mo>&times;</mo> <mn>1</mn> <msup> <mn>0</mn> <mn>3</mn> </msup> <msup> <mo>moles/m</mo> <mn>3</mn> </msup> </mrow> </mfenced> </mrow> </math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (06 Apr)","image":null},{"id":29301,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Electrochemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"Given: pH = 5, so $[H^+] = 10^{-5}$ M; G = $4 \\times 10^{-5}$ S; A = 1 cm²; l = 15 cm<br>Cell constant = l/A = 15 cm⁻¹<br>Specific conductivity: $\\kappa = G \\times (l/A) = 4 \\times 10^{-5} \\times 15 = 6 \\times 10^{-4}$ S/cm<br>For weak acid HX: $[H^+] = C\\alpha = 10^{-5}$ M<br>Using $\\kappa = \\frac{C\\alpha \\times \\Lambda°_m}{1000}$<br>$\\Lambda°_m = \\frac{1000 \\times \\kappa}{C\\alpha} = \\frac{1000 \\times 6 \\times 10^{-4}}{10^{-5}} = 6 \\times 10^4$ S cm² mol⁻¹<br>Converting: $\\Lambda°_m = 6 \\times 10^4 \\times 10^{-4} = 6$ S m² mol⁻¹","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (21 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29491,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Electrochemistry","question":"","options":["$0.26 \\mathrm{~V}$","$0.399 \\mathrm{~V}$","$-0.339 \\mathrm{~V}$","$-0.26 \\mathrm{~V}$"],"answer":0,"solution":"$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& \\text { As } \\mathrm{E}_{\\mathrm{Cr} / \\mathrm{cr}^{3+}}^0=-0.72 \\mathrm{~V} \\text { and } \\mathrm{E}_{\\mathrm{Fe}^{2+} / \\mathrm{Fe}}^0=-0.42 \\mathrm{~V} \\\\\n& 2 \\mathrm{Cr}+3 \\mathrm{Fe}^{2+} \\longrightarrow 3 \\mathrm{Fe}+2 \\mathrm{Cr}^{3+} \\\\\n& \\mathrm{E}_{\\text {cell }}=\\mathrm{E}_{\\text {cell }}^0-\\frac{0.0591}{6} \\log \\frac{\\left(\\mathrm{Cr}^{3+}\\right)^2}{\\left(\\mathrm{Fe}^{2+}\\right)^3} \\\\\n& =(-0.42+0.72)-\\frac{0.0591}{6} \\log \\frac{(0.1)^2}{(0.01)^3}=0.30-\\frac{0.0591}{6} \\log \\frac{(0.1)^2}{(0.01)^3} \\\\\n& =0.30-\\frac{0.0591}{6} \\log \\frac{10^{-2}}{10^{-6}}=0.30-\\frac{0.0591}{6} \\log 10^4 \\\\\n& \\mathrm{E}_{\\text {cell }}=0.2606 \\mathrm{~V}\n\\end{aligned}\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2008","image":null},{"id":29326,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Electrochemistry","question":"","options":["\\(\\Lambda_{\\mathrm{m}}-\\Lambda_{\\mathrm{m}}^0+\\mathrm{AC}^{\\frac{1}{2}}=0\\)","\\(\\Lambda_m^2 \\mathrm{C}-\\mathrm{K}_{\\mathrm{a}} \\Lambda_{\\mathrm{m}}^{\\circ 2}+\\mathrm{K}_{\\mathrm{a}} \\Lambda_{\\mathrm{m}} \\Lambda_{\\mathrm{m}}=0\\)","\\(\\Lambda^2{ }_m \\mathrm{C}+\\mathrm{K}_{\\mathrm{a}} \\Lambda_{\\mathrm{m}}^{\\circ 2}-\\mathrm{K}_{\\mathrm{a}} \\Lambda_{\\mathrm{m}} \\Lambda_{\\mathrm{m}}^{\\circ}=0\\)","\\(\\Lambda_{\\mathrm{m}}-\\Lambda_{\\mathrm{m}}^{\\circ}-\\mathrm{AC}^{\\frac{1}{2}}=0\\)"],"answer":1,"solution":"$\\begin{aligned} & \\mathrm{HA}(\\mathrm{aq}) \\rightleftharpoons \\mathrm{H}^{+}(\\mathrm{aq})+\\mathrm{A}^{-}(\\mathrm{aq}) \\\\ & \\mathrm{K}_{\\mathrm{a}}=\\frac{\\alpha^2 \\mathrm{C}}{1-\\alpha} \\\\ & \\alpha^2 \\mathrm{C}+\\mathrm{K}_{\\mathrm{a}} \\alpha-\\mathrm{K}_{\\mathrm{a}}=0 \\\\ & \\left(\\frac{\\lambda_{\\mathrm{m}}}{\\lambda_{\\mathrm{m}}^{\\infty}}\\right)^2 \\mathrm{C}+\\mathrm{K}_{\\mathrm{a}} \\frac{\\lambda_{\\mathrm{m}}}{\\lambda_{\\mathrm{m}}^{\\infty}}-\\mathrm{K}_{\\mathrm{a}}=0 \\\\ & \\lambda_{\\mathrm{m}}^2 \\mathrm{C}+\\mathrm{K}_{\\mathrm{a}} \\lambda_{\\mathrm{m}} \\lambda_{\\mathrm{m}}^{\\infty}-\\mathrm{K}_{\\mathrm{a}}\\left(\\lambda_{\\mathrm{m}}^{\\infty}\\right)^2=0\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (09 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29504,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Electrochemistry","question":"","options":["$128 \\mathrm{~S} \\mathrm{~cm}^2 \\mathrm{~mol}^{-1}$","$302 \\mathrm{~S} \\mathrm{~cm}^2 \\mathrm{~mol}^{-1}$","$278 \\mathrm{~S} \\mathrm{~cm}^2 \\mathrm{~mol}^{-1}$","$176 \\mathrm{~S} \\mathrm{~cm}^2 \\mathrm{~mol}^{-1}$"],"answer":0,"solution":"$\\Lambda_{\\mathrm{NaCl}}^{\\circ}=\\lambda_{\\mathrm{Na}}^{\\circ}+\\lambda_{\\mathrm{Cl}}^{\\circ}=126 \\ldots(1)$\n$\\Lambda_{\\mathrm{KBr}}^{\\circ}=\\lambda_{\\mathrm{K}^{+}}^{\\circ}+\\lambda_{\\mathrm{Br}^{-}}^{\\circ}=152$\n$\\Lambda_{\\mathrm{KCl}}^{\\circ}=\\lambda_{\\mathrm{K}^{+}}^{\\circ}+\\lambda_{\\mathrm{Cl}^{-}}^{\\circ}=150$\n$\\Lambda_{\\mathrm{NaBr}}^{\\circ}=\\lambda_{\\mathrm{Na}}^{\\circ}+\\lambda_{\\mathrm{Br}^{-}}^{\\circ}$\n$\\Lambda_{\\mathrm{NaBr}}^{\\circ}=126+152-150=128$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2004","image":null},{"id":29331,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Electrochemistry","question":"","options":["\\(\\mathrm{Ag}\\left|\\mathrm{AgCl}_{(\\text {s) }}\\right| \\mathrm{KCl}_{\\text {(soln.) }}\\left|\\mathrm{AgNO}_{3 \\text { (aq.) }}\\right| \\mathrm{Ag}\\)","\\(\\mathrm{Pt}\\left|\\mathrm{H}_{2(\\mathrm{~g})}\\right| \\mathrm{HCl}_{\\text {(soln.) }}\\left|\\mathrm{AgCl}_{(\\mathrm{s})}\\right| \\mathrm{Ag}\\)","\\(\\mathrm{Pt}\\left|\\mathrm{H}_{2(\\mathrm{~g})}\\right| \\mathrm{KCl}_{(\\text {soln. })}\\left|\\mathrm{AgCl}_{(s)}\\right| \\mathrm{Ag}\\)","\\(\\mathrm{Pt}\\left|\\mathrm{H}_{2(\\mathrm{~g})}\\right| \\mathrm{HCl}_{\\text {(soln.) }}\\left|\\mathrm{AgNO}_{3(\\mathrm{aq})}\\right| \\mathrm{Ag}\\)"],"answer":2,"solution":"Anodic half cell\n$\\underline{\\text { Gas - gas ion electrode }}$\n$\\frac{1}{2} \\mathrm{H}_{2(\\mathrm{~g})} \\rightarrow \\mathrm{H}_{(\\mathrm{aq})}^{+}+\\mathrm{e}^{-}$\nCathodic Reaction\nMetal-metal insoluble salt anion electrode\n$\\mathrm{Ag}_{(\\mathrm{aq})}^{+}+\\mathrm{e}^{-} \\rightarrow \\mathrm{Ag}_{(\\mathrm{s})}$\n$\\begin{aligned} & \\mathrm{AgCl}_{(\\mathrm{s})} \\rightleftharpoons \\mathrm{Ag}_{(\\mathrm{aq})}^{+}+\\mathrm{Cl}_{(\\mathrm{aq})}^{-} \\\\ & \\mathrm{AgCl}_{(\\mathrm{s})}+\\mathrm{e}^{-} \\rightarrow \\mathrm{Ag}_{(\\mathrm{s})}+\\mathrm{Cl}_{(\\mathrm{aq})}^{-}\\end{aligned}$\nOverall redox reaction\n$\\frac{1}{2} \\mathrm{H}_{2(\\mathrm{~g})}+\\mathrm{AgCl}_{(\\mathrm{s})} \\rightarrow \\mathrm{H}_{(\\mathrm{aq})}^{+}+\\mathrm{Cl}_{(\\mathrm{aq})}^{-}+\\mathrm{Ag}_{(\\mathrm{s})}$\nCell Representation\nPt $\\left|\\mathrm{H}_{2(\\mathrm{~g})}\\right| \\mathrm{kCl}_{\\text {(sol) }}\\left|\\mathrm{AgCl}_{\\text {(s) }}\\right| \\mathrm{Ag}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (08 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29294,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Electrochemistry","question":"","options":["If $\\mathrm{c}_{1}$ is present at cathode, then $\\mathrm{c}_{1}<\\mathrm{c}_{2}$.","If $\\mathrm{c}_{1}$ is present at anode, then $\\mathrm{c}_{1}>\\mathrm{c}_{2}$.","If $c_{1}$ is present at cathode, then $c_{1}>c_{2}$.","If $\\mathrm{c}_{1}$ is present at anode, then $\\mathrm{c}_{1}=\\mathrm{c}_{2}$."],"answer":2,"solution":"The given setup is a concentration cell with identical electrodes (M) and different electrolyte concentrations ($c_1$ and $c_2$).<br>For a concentration cell, the standard cell potential $E^0_{cell} = 0$.<br>The cell reactions are:<br>Anode: $M(s) \\rightarrow M^+(c_{anode}) + e^-$<br>Cathode: $M^+(c_{cathode}) + e^- \\rightarrow M(s)$<br>Net reaction: $M^+(c_{cathode}) \\rightarrow M^+(c_{anode})$<br>Using the Nernst equation at $298\\text{ K}$:<br>$E_{cell} = E^0_{cell} - \\frac{0.0591}{n} \\log \\frac{c_{anode}}{c_{cathode}}$<br>$E_{cell} = 0 - 0.0591 \\log \\frac{c_{anode}}{c_{cathode}}$<br>For a positive cell potential ($E_{cell} > 0$), the term $\\log \\frac{c_{anode}}{c_{cathode}}$ must be negative.<br>This requires $\\frac{c_{anode}}{c_{cathode}} < 1$, which means $c_{cathode} > c_{anode}$.<br>If $c_1$ is present at the cathode and $c_2$ is at the anode, then for $E_{cell} > 0$, we must have $c_1 > c_2$.<br>Checking the options:<br>(1) If $c_1$ is at cathode, $c_1 < c_2$ (Incorrect)<br>(2) If $c_1$ is at anode, $c_1 > c_2$ (Incorrect, would require $c_2 > c_1$)<br>(3) If $c_1$ is at cathode, $c_1 > c_2$ (Correct)<br>(4) If $c_1$ is at anode, $c_1 = c_2$ (Incorrect, $E_{cell}$ would be zero)","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (23 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29316,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Electrochemistry","question":"","options":["\\(\\mathrm{E}_{\\mathrm{Pb}^{4+} / \\mathrm{Pb}^{2+}}^{\\ominus}=+1.67 \\mathrm{~V}\\)","\\(\\mathrm{E}_{\\mathrm{Sn}^{4+} / \\mathrm{Sn}^{2+}}^{\\ominus}=+1.15 \\mathrm{~V}\\)","\\(\\mathrm{E}_{\\mathrm{Al}^{3+} / \\mathrm{Al}}^{\\ominus}=-1.66 \\mathrm{~V}\\)","\\(\\mathrm{E}_{\\mathrm{Tl}^{3+}\\mathrm{/Tl}}^{\\ominus}=1.26 \\mathrm{~V}\\)"],"answer":0,"solution":"The element having strongest oxidising capacity will have highest value of standard reduction potential","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (29 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29352,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Electrochemistry","question":"","options":["Coating of iron surface by tin prevents rusting, even if the tin coating is peeling off.","When <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>pH</mi></math> lies above <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>9</mn></math> or <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>10</mn></math> , rusting of iron does not take place.","Dissolved acidic oxides <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> in water act as catalyst in the process of rusting.","Rusting of iron is envisaged as setting up of electrochemical cell on the surface of iron object."],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Rusting refers to the creation of rust on the surface of iron objects or structures, which is a mixture of iron oxides. In a water-rich environment, rust is created through a redox interaction between oxygen and iron (or high levels of moisture). The creation of a layer of a red, flaky substance that quickly crumbles into a powder characterises the rusting of iron.</p><p>As the tin coating is peeled off, then iron is exposed to the atmosphere.</p><p>Because rusting occurs as a result of a chemical interaction between iron and air in the presence of moisture, it is a chemical alteration. The iron would not have rusted and gained a brown texture from its dull grey one if the chemical interaction between them had not occurred. As a result, a new substance known as rust forms on the surface of iron.</p><p>Hence, the answer is A.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (27 Jan Shift 2)","image":null}]